{"title_page": "The Prayer Cycle", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Prayer Cycle\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jonathan Elias]]<br>featuring various artists\n| cover      = Prayer Cycle.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 23, 1999 <small>(U.S.)</small>\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = Choral\n| length     = 51:29\n| label      = [[Sony Classical Records|Sony Classical]]\n| producer   = Jonathan Elias, [[R. Walt Vincent]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''The Prayer Cycle''''' is a choral/orchestral album by American film and television composer [[Jonathan Elias]], and was released by [[Sony Classical Records]] in the United States on March 23, 1999.\n\nThe project, recorded and mixed by co-producer [[R. Walt Vincent]], consists of a nine-part contemporary [[choral symphony]] in thirteen languages ([[Magyar language|Hungarian]], [[Bambara language|Mali]], [[Swahili language|Swahili]], [[Duala language|Dwala]], [[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]], [[German language|German]], [[French language|French]], [[Urdu]], [[Latin]], [[English language|English]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]). In the album's liner notes, Elias described the work as \"a set of nine ''adagio'' prayers\" that were influenced by his \"personal views\" about the future of humankind and the power of prayer across cultures. The contributing musical artists \"used poems [he] wrote as inspiration, interpreting the words in their own way, in many different languages and chants.\"\n\nThe featured vocalists were [[Alanis Morissette]], [[Salif Keita]], [[Perry Farrell]], [[Richard Bona]], [[Yungchen Lhamo]], [[Liz Constantine]], [[Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]], [[Mah Damba]], [[James Taylor]], [[Ofra Haza]], and [[Linda Ronstadt]]. The featured instrumentalists were [[John Williams (guitarist)|John Williams]] ([[guitar]]), [[Martin Tillman]] (processed [[cello]]), and Ethan James ([[hurdy gurdy]]). The featured artists were accompanied by [[English Chamber Orchestra|The English Chamber Orchestra & Chorus]], conducted by [[Lawrence Schwartz]], and [[American Boychoir School|The American Boychoir]], featuring [[Devin Provenzano]].\n\nMusic from ''The Prayer Cycle'' was featured on the 1999 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] documentary series called \"The Century\", which aired in six parts March 29 and April 1, 3, 5, 8 and 10.\n\n''The Prayer Cycle'' was played in its entirety for two ''[[Music from the Hearts of Space]]'' programs, \"The Prayer Cycle\" (program 536, originally aired September 10, 1999)<ref>[https://v4.hos.com/programs/details/536 Program listing for ''The Prayer Cycle''] on the official [https://v4.hos.com Hearts of Space] website.</ref> and again as \"Terror and Hope\" (program 605, originally aired September 21, 2001) in response to the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]].<ref>[https://v4.hos.com/programs/details/605 Program listing for \"Terror and Hope\"] on the official Hearts of Space website.</ref> It has only ever been performed live once, by the Branford High School choir at Woolsey Hall in [[New Haven, Connecticut]]. The piece was conducted by choir director Cathyann Roding and performed by the choir (including featured soloists) and a 45-piece orchestra. <ref>{{cite web |first=Jenn |last=McCullough |title=BHS Choir to Perform The Prayer Cycle at Woolsey Hall |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/branford/bhs-choir-to-perform-the-prayer-cycle-at-woolsey-hall |website=Branford, CT Patch |publisher=Patch |date=April 23, 2013 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116130659/https://patch.com/connecticut/branford/bhs-choir-to-perform-the-prayer-cycle-at-woolsey-hall |archive-date=16 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll information appears as indicated in the album's liner notes.\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n